/************************************************************************/
*                                                                        *
*                                                                        *
*                       Manual for Sea Shell ;)                          *
*                                                                        *
*                                                                        *
/************************************************************************/


BUILT IN FUNCTIONS:

help -   prints information regarding shell commands and usage
         usage: help

/************************************************************************/

cd -     Checks the directory path given. If cd is used with "..", it
        moves the user down one level in the filesystem. cd used by it
        self moves the user to the HOME path.

usage:  cd <directory path>, cd <..>, cd < >

/************************************************************************/

exit -  allows the user to exit the shell program, no arguments are required

usage:  exit

/************************************************************************/

clear - clears the text filling up the terminal screen.

usage:  clear

/************************************************************************/

echo - allows the user to print a entered string to stdout (the command 
       prompt). You can also use echo by itself, though nothing happens
       
usage: echo <String>

/************************************************************************/

environ - prints all of the strings for the environment, information 
          includes the path variable name as well as information about
          the terminal window itself.

usage:    environ

/************************************************************************/

ls -    lists all of the files in the currently directory. ls can be used
        with a number of different arguments to print file permissions
        and other important information about the files in the directory

*Current supported ls commands aside from just ls are listed below:

ls -a   lists all of the entries starting with "."

ls -d   list the directory entries instead of the contents

ls -l   uses a long listing format

ls -al  list all entries starting with . with a long list format

ls -g   just like ls -l only it does not list the owner of the file

ls -m   fill width with a coma separated list of entries 

ls -o   like -l. but do not list group information

ls -r   reverse the order while sorting

ls -s   prints the size of each file in blocks

ls -t   sorts by modification time

ls -x   list entries by lines instead of coulmns.

ls -1   lists one file per line.


usage: ls, ls -<argument 2> 

/************************************************************************/

pause -     pauses the running of the shell until the enter key is pressed

usage:      pause

/************************************************************************/

more -      more allows for the user to read contents of a specified file

usage:      more <filename>

/************************************************************************/

sh -        sh is used to execute a .sh file otherwise known as a batch
            file. This is synonymous with 'bash'

usage:      sh <file.sh>

/************************************************************************/

bash -      bash is sued to execute a .sh file otherwise known as a batch
            file. This is synonymous with 'sh'

usage:      bash <file.sh>

/************************************************************************/

pwd -       pwd is used for the user to print the current working directory
            of the file system.

usage:      pwd

/************************************************************************/


/************************************************************************/
*                                                                        *
*                       USAGE OF PROGRAM COMMANDS                        *
*                                                                        *
/************************************************************************/

Pipe -   can be used to use one command as anothers input

usage:   <cmd> | <cmd>

/************************************************************************/

I/O redirection - allows for input or output to be redirected in the
                  following usage:

usage:          <cmd> <args> > <output>
                <cmd> <args> < <input> > <output>

/************************************************************************/

Background execution -  Allows user to have program execute in the
                        background while still using the command line.

usage:                  <args> &

/************************************************************************/